<p>If you are researching products to sell online, you have probably encountered three names: Helium 10, Jungle Scout, and Kaldon. All three help you find profitable products. But they take very different approaches to what happens after you find one.</p>

<p>This is a fair comparison. We built Kaldon, so we are obviously biased. But we will be honest about where each platform excels and where it falls short. You can make your own decision.</p>

<h2>The Quick Summary</h2>

<p><strong>Helium 10</strong> is the most comprehensive Amazon-specific toolkit. It excels at keyword research, listing optimization, and Amazon PPC management. If you are an established Amazon seller optimizing existing listings, Helium 10 has the deepest feature set.</p>

<p><strong>Jungle Scout</strong> is the most popular product research tool. It is simpler than Helium 10, with a focus on product discovery and supplier sourcing. If you are just starting and want a straightforward research tool, Jungle Scout is the easiest to learn.</p>

<p><strong>Kaldon</strong> is a full-pipeline platform that starts with research and continues through brand building, content creation, store deployment, and growth optimization. If you want one platform that takes you from idea to revenue, Kaldon does the most.</p>

<h2>Product Research</h2>

<p><strong>Helium 10:</strong> Black Box product finder, Xray Chrome extension, Trendster for seasonal analysis. Data is Amazon-specific and very granular. You can filter by revenue, review count, price, category, and dozens of other criteria. The data is excellent, but interpreting it requires experience.</p>

<p><strong>Jungle Scout:</strong> Product Database, Opportunity Finder, Chrome extension. Similar data to Helium 10 but with a simpler interface. The Opportunity Score gives you a quick viability assessment. Supplier Database is unique to Jungle Scout and genuinely useful.</p>

<p><strong>Kaldon:</strong> AI-powered analysis engine that evaluates products across 9 data sources (Amazon, Walmart, Google Trends, social media, and more). Instead of giving you raw data to interpret, Kaldon generates a viability score, AI product mockups, a competitive breakdown, and a step-by-step action plan. The output is a decision, not a spreadsheet.</p>

<p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Helium 10 wins on data depth for Amazon. Jungle Scout wins on simplicity. Kaldon wins on actionability and multi-marketplace coverage.</p>

<h2>What Happens After Research</h2>

<p>This is where the three platforms diverge completely.</p>

<p><strong>Helium 10:</strong> After research, Helium 10 helps you optimize your Amazon listing (Scribbles, Frankenstein), manage PPC (Adtomic), and track keywords (Keyword Tracker). It is Amazon-focused end to end. If you want to build a brand, create content, or sell on other channels, you need additional tools.</p>

<p><strong>Jungle Scout:</strong> After research, Jungle Scout helps you find suppliers (Supplier Database) and optimize your Amazon listing. That is essentially where it stops. For brand building, content, DTC, and marketing, you need a separate stack.</p>

<p><strong>Kaldon:</strong> After research, Kaldon takes you through four additional phases: Build (brand identity, logo, brand board), Create (content calendar, video studio, landing pages, one-off composer), Launch (store deployment, marketplace listings, blog engine), and Grow (ad campaigns, performance analytics). Every phase uses data from the previous phase.</p>

<p><strong>Verdict:</strong> If you only sell on Amazon and only need research and optimization, Helium 10 or Jungle Scout are sufficient. If you want to build a complete business across multiple channels, Kaldon is the only platform that does it all.</p>

<h2>Pricing Comparison</h2>

<p><strong>Helium 10:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Free: Very limited (2 days of some tools)</li>
  <li>Starter: $39/mo (basic research only)</li>
  <li>Platinum: $79/mo (most popular, full research + optimization)</li>
  <li>Diamond: $229/mo (adds Adtomic PPC management)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Jungle Scout:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Basic: $49/mo (single user, limited history)</li>
  <li>Suite: $69/mo (full features, 1 user)</li>
  <li>Professional: $129/mo (multi-user, API access)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Kaldon:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Free: 2 analyses, full report quality</li>
  <li>Single Analysis: $29 one-time</li>
  <li>Growth: $149/mo (25 analyses, 3 brands, full pipeline)</li>
  <li>Pro: $249/mo (60 analyses, 5 brands, priority AI)</li>
  <li>Scale: $399/mo (unlimited analyses, 10 brands, agency features)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>The real cost comparison:</strong> Helium 10 Platinum ($79/mo) or Jungle Scout Suite ($69/mo) only covers research. To match Kaldon's full pipeline, you would need to add Canva Pro ($15/mo), Jasper ($49/mo), Later ($25/mo), Shopify ($39/mo + apps), and more. Total: $250-400/mo for the equivalent of Kaldon Growth at $149/mo.</p>

<h2>Who Should Use What</h2>

<p><strong>Use Helium 10 if:</strong> You are an established Amazon seller with existing listings that need optimization. You want the deepest Amazon-specific data. You are comfortable interpreting raw data and building your own strategy.</p>

<p><strong>Use Jungle Scout if:</strong> You are a beginner who wants the simplest product research experience. You need supplier sourcing. You are Amazon-only and do not plan to go multi-channel.</p>

<p><strong>Use Kaldon if:</strong> You want one platform that takes you from product idea to revenue. You want to build a real brand, not just an Amazon listing. You want to sell on Amazon, Walmart, and DTC. You value actionable intelligence over raw data.</p>

<h2>Can You Use Them Together?</h2>

<p>Yes. Many sellers use Helium 10 or Jungle Scout for Amazon-specific keyword tracking while using Kaldon for the full pipeline. However, most find that Kaldon's research capabilities cover their needs and they can consolidate to one subscription.</p>

<p>The best way to decide is to try them. Kaldon offers 2 free analyses. Helium 10 and Jungle Scout both offer free trials. Run the same product through all three and compare the output.</p>

